> **APJ ABDUL KALAM TECHNOLOGICAL UNIVERSITY (KTU) | 2024 SCHEME**
> - **Course:** PBEOT504 - DATABASE MANAGEMENT SYSTEM
> - **Module:** Module 2
> - **Topic:** Accessing SQL from a Programming Language

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

**Accessing SQL from a Programming Language** refers to the set of techniques, standards, and Application Programming Interfaces (APIs) that allow a host programming language (such as **C**, **C++**, **Java**, **COBOL**, or **Python**) to communicate with a **Database Management System (DBMS)** in order to issue **SQL (Structured Query Language)** statements, retrieve results, and manipulate persistent data.

In the KTU 2024 Scheme parlance, this topic belongs to the broader module of **SQL and Procedural Languages**, where the focus is on bridging the *declarative* world of relational databases with the *imperative* world of general-purpose programming. The three principal standards-based approaches covered in the syllabus are:

1. **Embedded SQL** (static and dynamic) ŌĆö defined originally in the **SQL/PSM** and **SQL-92** standards.
2. **Call Level Interface (CLI)** ŌĆö a function-call based API; commercialized as **ODBC (Open Database Connectivity)** and **JDBC (Java Database Connectivity)**.
3. **SQL/CLI Standard** ŌĆö the formal ISO standard underlying ODBC/JDBC.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight (PBEOT504 ŌĆō Module 2):**
> The 2024 scheme explicitly tests the student's ability to **differentiate between embedded SQL and dynamic SQL**, write **cursor-based programs** to handle multi-row results, and **trace the JDBC execution flow** (DriverManager ŌåÆ Connection ŌåÆ Statement ŌåÆ ResultSet).

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy ŌĆö "The Diplomat at the United Nations"

Imagine SQL is **French** (a beautiful, precise, rule-bound language) and your programming language is **Japanese** (a structured, powerful, expressive language). The two languages have **almost no common grammar, syntax, or vocabulary** ŌĆö a phenomenon engineers call the **Impedance Mismatch**.

Now, suppose a Japanese delegate needs to address a French-speaking assembly. There are **three possible solutions**, and each maps exactly to the three technical approaches we study:

| Real-World Solution | Technical Approach |
|---|---|
| Hire a **pre-translator** who converts the entire speech in advance and hands over a written manuscript before the meeting. | **Embedded (Static) SQL** ŌĆö SQL is *preprocessed* and embedded directly inside the source code. |
| Hire a **live interpreter** who listens to the speech and translates sentence-by-sentence as the delegate speaks. | **Dynamic SQL** ŌĆö SQL strings are *constructed at runtime* and executed on demand. |
| Provide the delegate with a **standardized microphone + protocol handbook** so the delegate can speak into a microphone and the system handles translation automatically. | **CLI / API approach (ODBC, JDBC)** ŌĆö a *function-call interface* with a standardized driver. |

> [!NOTE]
> **Impedance Mismatch (Impedance Mismatch Problem):** The fundamental conflict between the **set-oriented, declarative** nature of SQL (which operates on *entire relations* at once) and the **record-oriented, imperative** nature of host languages (which operate on *one record/variable* at a time). This is the central problem that "Accessing SQL from a Programming Language" attempts to solve.

### 1.3 Why Do We Need This Bridge?

SQL alone is **not Turing-complete**. It lacks:
- Variables with arbitrary user-defined types.
- Looping constructs (in standard SQL, before SQL/PSM).
- Rich I/O, GUI integration, and network handling.
- Ability to perform complex business logic, file handling, or OS interaction.

Hence, **real-world applications** (Banking software, ERP systems, e-commerce portals, attendance systems) **must combine** the strengths of a host language (logic, control flow, I/O) with the strengths of SQL (data persistence, set-processing, security).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Standard Metrics & Definitions (Bolded for Emphasis):**
> - **Impedance Mismatch:** The structural and type-system divergence between SQL relations and host-language data structures.
> - **Cursor:** A *pointer* to a specific row within a result set, used to iterate row-by-row.
> - **SQLCA (SQL Communication Area):** A *system-managed structure* that holds the status (error codes, warnings) of the most recent SQL operation in embedded SQL.
> - **Precompiler / SQL Translator:** A *preprocessor* that scans host-language source code for SQL statements and converts them into appropriate function calls before normal compilation.
> - **Driver:** A *vendor-specific software module* (in JDBC/ODBC) that translates generic API calls into the native protocol of a specific DBMS.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 The Three Architectural Approaches ŌĆö A Structured Breakdown

#### Approach 1: Embedded SQL (Static Embedded SQL)

Embedded SQL is the **oldest and most tightly integrated** approach, standardized in **SQL-86 / SQL-89 / SQL-92** under the name **SQL/Embedded**.

**Operational Lifecycle (The "Why" and "How"):**

1. **Source Code Authoring:** The programmer writes a host program (e.g., C, COBOL) and inserts SQL statements prefixed with the marker `EXEC SQL` (or `EXEC SQL BEGIN DECLARE SECTION`, etc.).
2. **Preprocessing:** Before normal compilation, an **SQL precompiler (preprocessor)** scans the source. It identifies all `EXEC SQL` blocks.
3. **Translation:** Each SQL block is translated into **function calls** to the DBMS's runtime library. Host variables are bound to SQL parameters. The `EXEC SQL` prefix is removed; the result is pure host-language code.
4. **Normal Compilation:** The generated C/C++ code is fed to the standard compiler, which produces an executable.
5. **Execution & SQLCA:** At runtime, the SQL statements execute. Errors and warnings are reported back to the program through the **SQLCA** structure.

**Why use it?** Performance ŌĆö the SQL is *known at compile time*, so the DBMS can **prepare an execution plan once** and reuse it, which is far faster than parsing on every execution.

> [!NOTE]
> **The "DECLARE SECTION":** In languages like C, this is the `EXEC SQL BEGIN DECLARE SECTION;` ... `EXEC SQL END DECLARE SECTION;` block inside which all host variables used by SQL must be declared. This is necessary because C variable declarations have no SQL type information, so the precompiler must know which variables participate in SQL.

#### Approach 2: Dynamic SQL

When the **exact SQL statement is not known until runtime** (e.g., the user types a custom search query in a form), we cannot precompile. We use Dynamic SQL.

**Operational Lifecycle:**

1. The program constructs the SQL statement as a **string variable** at runtime.
2. The statement is **prepared** (`PREPARE` command) ŌĆö the DBMS parses, validates, and optimizes it.
3. The program then **executes** the prepared statement (`EXECUTE` command).
4. Alternatively, a single command `EXECUTE IMMEDIATE` combines both steps for one-time execution.

**Why use it?** Flexibility ŌĆö handles user-driven, ad-hoc queries that cannot be hardcoded.

#### Approach 3: Call Level Interface (CLI) ŌĆö ODBC and JDBC

A **function-call library** that the host program links against. No preprocessor is needed. The program constructs SQL strings and calls library functions like `SQLExecDirect()`, `SQLFetch()`, `SQLBindColumn()` (ODBC) or `executeQuery()`, `next()`, `getString()` (JDBC).

**Why use it?** Portability and flexibility ŌĆö the same program can connect to Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, etc., by simply swapping drivers.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **SQL/CLI Standard:** The ISO/IEC 9075-3 standard that defines a CLI for SQL. Microsoft **ODBC** is the de-facto commercial realization. **JDBC** is the Java-specific realization of the same conceptual model.

### 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Symbol / Term | Standard / Definition | Unit / Scope | Boundary Conditions |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Impedance Mismatch | $M_{imp}$ | Set-oriented vs record-oriented conflict | Conceptual | Always present in non-trivial SQL-host interaction |
| SQL Precompiler | $P_{sql}$ | Translates `EXEC SQL` blocks into function calls | Tool | Required only for Embedded SQL |
| SQLCA | $S_{ca}$ | Status report structure (warning, error, row count) | Bytes | Updated after every embedded SQL statement |
| Cursor | $C_{r}$ | Pointer to a row in a multi-row result set | Logical | Needed when query returns more than 1 row |
| Cursor States | $S_c$ | Declared, Opened, Fetched, Closed | Lifecycle | Must be CLOSED to free resources |
| JDBC Driver Types | $T_d$ | Type 1 (JDBC-ODBC bridge), Type 2 (Native), Type 3 (Network), Type 4 (Pure Java) | Classification | Type 4 is the modern standard |
| Connection URL | $U_{con}$ | `jdbc:subprotocol:subname` | String format | Vendor-specific subprotocol |
| Prepared Statement | $P_{stmt}$ | Precompiled parameterized SQL | Object | Reusable, prevents SQL injection |
| Transaction Isolation | $I_{tx}$ | READ UNCOMMITTED $\vert$ READ COMMITTED $\vert$ REPEATABLE READ $\vert$ SERIALIZABLE | Level | Set via `Connection.setTransactionIsolation()` |
| ResultSet Concurrency | $C_{rs}$ | `ResultSet.CONCUR_READ_ONLY` $\vert$ `ResultSet.CONCUR_UPDATABLE` | Mode | Default is read-only |

> [!WARNING]
> In the KTU board valuation, the **impedance mismatch** must be cited by name. Writing "they are different" is **not acceptable**; you must use the exact phrase **"impedance mismatch"** to score full marks.

### 2.3 Engineering Real-World Utility

| Industry Domain | How SQL-from-Code Is Used |
|---|---|
| **Banking & FinTech** | Embedded SQL in COBOL for core transaction processing; JDBC in Java for mobile/internet banking. |
| **E-Commerce (Amazon, Flipkart)** | JDBC/ODBC for order processing, inventory, and payment systems. |
| **Healthcare (HIS)** | Embedded SQL + dynamic SQL for reporting tools that allow doctors to query patient data. |
| **Telecom (Billing Systems)** | High-throughput batch processing using static embedded SQL for maximum speed. |
| **IoT & Sensor Data** | Lightweight ODBC drivers to push telemetry data into time-series DBs. |
| **Web Applications (LAMP, MEAN)** | JDBC/PDO (PHP) for client-tier to database-tier connectivity. |

### 2.4 Detailed Comparison: Embedded SQL vs. Dynamic SQL vs. CLI

| Feature | Embedded (Static) SQL | Dynamic SQL | CLI (ODBC/JDBC) |
|---|---|---|---|
| **When SQL is known** | Compile time | Runtime | Runtime |
| **Preprocessor needed?** | Yes | No (but `PREPARE` does similar work) | No |
| **Performance** | Fastest (precompiled plan) | Slower (parsed on every execution, unless using `PREPARE`) | Moderate |
| **Flexibility** | Lowest | Highest | High |
| **Portability across DBMS** | Low (DBMS-specific precompiler) | Higher | Highest (driver-based) |
| **Syntax** | `EXEC SQL` prefix | String + `EXECUTE` | Function calls / method calls |
| **Impedance mismatch handling** | Cursors | Cursors (if needed) | ResultSet iteration |
| **SQL Injection Risk** | Low (statements hardcoded) | High (string concatenation) | High (unless `PreparedStatement` used) |
| **Typical Use Case** | High-performance batch | User-form-driven searches | General-purpose applications |
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations, Code Walkthroughs & Analytical Matrix

> [!NOTE]
> The "derivations" in this section are **algorithmic step-by-step traces** of how each method executes, including sample programs in C (for Embedded SQL) and Java (for JDBC). Every line is explained to satisfy KTU's "show the working" valuation pattern.

### 3.1 Derivation: Lifecycle of an Embedded SQL Program (in C)

This is the canonical KTU model. We trace the journey of the program from `source.c` to `executable`.

$$
\text{Step 0: Programmer writes } P_{src} = \text{source.c} \text{ with EXEC SQL blocks}
$$

$$
\text{Step 1: SQL Precompiler } (P_{sql}) \text{ scans } P_{src} \text{ and emits } P_{trans} = \text{source.c (translated)}
$$

$$
\text{Step 2: Standard C Compiler } (C_{comp}) \text{ compiles } P_{trans} \text{ to } O = \text{object.o}
$$

$$
\text{Step 3: Linker } (L) \text{ links } O \text{ with SQL runtime library } R_{sql} \text{ to produce } E = \text{executable}
$$

$$
\therefore \quad E \;=\; L(C_{comp}(P_{sql}(P_{src})), R_{sql})
$$

#### Worked Example: Embedded SQL Program to Update a Student Record

```c
/* === STEP-BY-STEP EMBEDDED SQL PROGRAM === */

#include <stdio.h>

/* Tell the precompiler we are using SQL */
EXEC SQL INCLUDE SQLCA;

/* Declare host variables that SQL will see */
EXEC SQL BEGIN DECLARE SECTION;
    int  student_id;
    char student_name[51];
    char message[100];
    float new_marks;
EXEC SQL END DECLARE SECTION;

int main() {

    /* Read inputs from user */
    printf("Enter Student ID: ");  scanf("%d", &student_id);
    printf("Enter new marks: ");   scanf("%f", &new_marks);

    /* Connect to the database */
    EXEC SQL CONNECT TO university_db USER sa USING password;

    /* Update a single row */
    EXEC SQL UPDATE Student
        SET marks = :new_marks
        WHERE sid = :student_id;

    /* Check the SQLCA for status */
    if (SQLCA.sqlcode == 0) {
        sprintf(message, "Update successful. Rows affected: %d", SQLCA.sqlerrd[2]);
        printf("%s\n", message);
    } else {
        printf("Error code: %d - %s\n", SQLCA.sqlcode, SQLCA.sqlerrm.sqlerrmc);
    }

    /* Disconnect */
    EXEC SQL DISCONNECT university_db;
    return 0;
}
```

**Step-by-Step Trace for the KTU Examiner:**

1. `EXEC SQL INCLUDE SQLCA;` ŌĆö The precompiler pastes the SQLCA structure definition into the code. This is **not executed**; it is a compile-time directive.
2. `EXEC SQL BEGIN/END DECLARE SECTION;` ŌĆö All variables between these two markers are accessible to SQL. The precompiler registers their types and memory addresses with the SQL runtime.
3. `EXEC SQL CONNECT TO ...;` ŌĆö Establishes a session. The precompiler converts this into a call to `SQLConnect()` or its equivalent in the runtime library.
4. `EXEC SQL UPDATE ...;` ŌĆö The colon prefix (`:new_marks`, `:student_id`) is the **host-variable indicator**. The precompiler generates code to bind these C variables as parameters to the SQL statement.
5. `SQLCA.sqlcode` ŌĆö A standard field: `0` = success, positive = warning (e.g., truncated string), negative = error.
6. `EXEC SQL DISCONNECT;` ŌĆö Terminates the session and releases resources.

### 3.2 Derivation: Cursor-Based Processing in Embedded SQL

A **cursor** is required whenever a `SELECT` statement may return **more than one row**, because host languages can only receive one row at a time.

**Algorithmic Trace:**

$$
\text{State}_0: \text{Cursor is DECLARED} \quad \longrightarrow \quad \text{no rows fetched}
$$

$$
\text{State}_1: \text{OPEN} \quad \longrightarrow \quad \text{DBMS evaluates query, builds result set}
$$

$$
\text{State}_2: \text{FETCH loop} \quad \longrightarrow \quad \text{one row at a time is transferred to host variables}
$$

$$
\text{State}_3: \text{CLOSE} \quad \longrightarrow \quad \text{result set is destroyed, resources freed}
$$

```c
/* === CURSOR EXAMPLE: List all students with marks > 50 === */

EXEC SQL BEGIN DECLARE SECTION;
    int  v_sid;
    char v_name[51];
    float v_marks;
EXEC SQL END DECLARE SECTION;

/* Step 1: DECLARE the cursor (no execution yet) */
EXEC SQL DECLARE high_scorer CURSOR FOR
    SELECT sid, sname, marks
    FROM Student
    WHERE marks > 50;

/* Step 2: OPEN the cursor (executes the query) */
EXEC SQL OPEN high_scorer;

/* Step 3: FETCH in a loop until no more rows (SQLCA.sqlcode == 100) */
while (1) {
    EXEC SQL FETCH high_scorer INTO :v_sid, :v_name, :v_marks;

    if (SQLCA.sqlcode == 100) break;  /* 100 = "no more rows" */
    if (SQLCA.sqlcode != 0) {
        printf("Error: %d\n", SQLCA.sqlcode);
        break;
    }
    printf("ID: %d | Name: %s | Marks: %.2f\n", v_sid, v_name, v_marks);
}

/* Step 4: CLOSE the cursor */
EXEC SQL CLOSE high_scorer;
```

**Why each step matters (for KTU valuation):**

- The `DECLARE` step is **purely declarative** ŌĆö no rows are fetched. Many students lose marks by confusing declaration with execution.
- The `OPEN` step is where the **DBMS actually runs the query** and materializes the result set (or sets up a pointer to it).
- The `SQLCODE = 100` condition is the **universal "end of data" indicator** in embedded SQL. This is a high-frequency KTU board question.
- The `CLOSE` step is **mandatory** to release locks and memory; failure to close causes resource leaks.

### 3.3 Derivation: Dynamic SQL Trace

**Use Case:** The user types a search condition in a form, and the program must construct and execute the corresponding SQL.

```c
/* === DYNAMIC SQL EXAMPLE === */

EXEC SQL BEGIN DECLARE SECTION;
    char sql_stmt[256];
    int  v_sid;
    char v_name[51];
    char search_name[51];
EXEC SQL END DECLARE SECTION;

printf("Enter partial name to search: ");
scanf("%s", search_name);

/* Step 1: Construct the SQL string at runtime */
sprintf(sql_stmt,
        "SELECT sid, sname FROM Student WHERE sname LIKE '%%%s%%'",
        search_name);

/* Step 2: PREPARE the statement (compile it once) */
EXEC SQL PREPARE dyn_stmt FROM :sql_stmt;

/* Step 3: DECLARE a cursor for the prepared statement */
EXEC SQL DECLARE dyn_cursor CURSOR FOR dyn_stmt;

/* Step 4: OPEN and FETCH */
EXEC SQL OPEN dyn_cursor;

while (1) {
    EXEC SQL FETCH dyn_cursor INTO :v_sid, :v_name;
    if (SQLCA.sqlcode == 100) break;
    printf("Found: %d, %s\n", v_sid, v_name);
}

EXEC SQL CLOSE dyn_cursor;
```

**Analytical Trace:**

$$
\text{User Input} \;\xrightarrow{\text{sprintf}}\; \text{SQL String} \;\xrightarrow{\text{PREPARE}}\; \text{Compiled Plan} \;\xrightarrow{\text{EXECUTE/OPEN}}\; \text{Result Set}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **EXECUTE IMMEDIATE vs. PREPARE + EXECUTE:**
> - `EXECUTE IMMEDIATE :sql_string;` ŌåÆ combines parse + execute in one step; use for **single-use** statements.
> - `PREPARE` + `EXECUTE` ŌåÆ parses once, executes many times; use when the **same statement is run repeatedly** with different parameters. This is the basis of `PreparedStatement` in JDBC.

### 3.4 Derivation: JDBC Execution Flow (Java-side)

JDBC is the most-tested topic in KTU 2024 KTU exams under this module. Trace the full lifecycle:

$$
\text{Java App} \;\xrightarrow{\text{load driver}}\; \text{DriverManager} \;\xrightarrow{\text{getConnection}}\; \text{Connection}
\;\xrightarrow{\text{createStatement}}\; \text{Statement} \;\xrightarrow{\text{executeQuery}}\; \text{ResultSet}
$$

#### Complete JDBC Code Walkthrough

```java
import java.sql.*;

public class StudentDB {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String url  = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/university_db";
        String user = "root";
        String pass = "password";

        // All JDBC resources declared outside try so finally can close them
        Connection conn = null;
        Statement  stmt = null;
        ResultSet  rs   = null;

        try {
            /* STEP 1: Load the driver (optional in JDBC 4.0+, but still good practice) */
            Class.forName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");

            /* STEP 2: Establish connection */
            conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass);
            conn.setAutoCommit(false);  // begin explicit transaction

            /* STEP 3: Create a statement */
            stmt = conn.createStatement();

            /* STEP 4a: Execute a SELECT query */
            rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT sid, sname, marks FROM Student WHERE marks > 50");

            /* STEP 5: Iterate the ResultSet */
            while (rs.next()) {
                int    id    = rs.getInt("sid");
                String name  = rs.getString("sname");
                float  marks = rs.getFloat("marks");
                System.out.println(id + " | " + name + " | " + marks);
            }

            /* STEP 4b: Execute an UPDATE via PreparedStatement (parameterized) */
            String updateSQL = "UPDATE Student SET marks = ? WHERE sid = ?";
            PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(updateSQL);
            pstmt.setFloat(1, 95.5f);
            pstmt.setInt(2, 101);
            int rows = pstmt.executeUpdate();
            System.out.println("Rows updated: " + rows);

            conn.commit();  // commit transaction
            pstmt.close();

        } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {
            System.out.println("Driver not found: " + e.getMessage());
        } catch (SQLException e) {
            try { if (conn != null) conn.rollback(); } catch (SQLException ex) { ex.printStackTrace(); }
            System.out.println("SQL Error: " + e.getMessage());
        } finally {
            /* STEP 6: Always close in reverse order: ResultSet ŌåÆ Statement ŌåÆ Connection */
            try { if (rs != null)    rs.close();    } catch (SQLException e) { }
            try { if (stmt != null)  stmt.close();  } catch (SQLException e) { }
            try { if (conn != null)  conn.close();  } catch (SQLException e) { }
        }
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Explanation (for full marks):**

1. `Class.forName(...)` ŌĆö Loads the driver class. Its static initializer registers itself with `DriverManager`. (Note: In JDBC 4.0+, this is auto-detected via `META-INF/services`, but KTU still expects you to mention it.)
2. `DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass)` ŌĆö The `DriverManager` iterates through all registered drivers, asks each if it accepts the URL, and returns the first match.
3. `conn.createStatement()` ŌĆö Creates a `Statement` object that will act as a *carrier* for the SQL string.
4. `stmt.executeQuery(...)` ŌĆö Returns a `ResultSet`, which is a **cursor-like object** with a pointer initially positioned *before the first row*.
5. `rs.next()` ŌĆö Moves the cursor to the next row; returns `false` when no more rows exist. This is **the most critical line** for the KTU exam.
6. `pstmt.setXxx(1, value)` ŌĆö Binds a value to the **1-based parameter index** of the `?` placeholder. Using `PreparedStatement` prevents **SQL injection** and improves performance through DBMS-side caching of the parsed plan.
7. The `finally` block ensures resources are **always released**, even on exception. The order of closing is the **reverse of opening** (LIFO).

### 3.5 Analytical Matrix: PreparedStatement vs. Statement

| Property | `Statement` | `PreparedStatement` |
|---|---|---|
| **SQL Injection** | Vulnerable | Safe (parameter binding, not string concat) |
| **Compilation** | Compiled on every execution | Compiled once, reused |
| **Performance (repeated calls)** | Slow | Fast |
| **Readability** | String concatenation mess | Clean `?` placeholders |
| **Use case** | One-time static DDL/DML | Repeated parameterized DML |
| **Inheritance** | Parent | Subclass of `Statement` |

### 3.6 Analytical Matrix: JDBC Driver Types

| Type | Name | Mechanism | Performance | Portability | KTU Note |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Type 1** | JDBC-ODBC Bridge | Translates JDBC ŌåÆ ODBC ŌåÆ Native | Slow | Low | Obsolete; removed in JDK 8 |
| **Type 2** | Native-API Driver | Uses vendor C/C++ library | Fast | Medium | Needs native DLL on client |
| **Type 3** | Network Protocol | Middleware server translates | Moderate | High | Rarely used today |
| **Type 4** | Thin Driver (Pure Java) | Direct DB protocol in Java | Fast | **Highest** | **Standard for modern apps** |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU frequently asks:** "Which JDBC driver type is most suitable for web applications and why?" The answer is **Type 4 (Pure Java / Thin Driver)** because it requires no native libraries, is platform-independent, and provides direct communication with the DBMS ŌĆö ideal for distributed web environments.
<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

<!-- SECTION_4_START -->
## 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

### 4.1 Diagram: End-to-End Architecture of "Accessing SQL from a Programming Language"

This Mermaid diagram maps the three approaches and shows how a host program interacts with a DBMS in each case.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Host Program Source Code] --> B{Which Access Method?}

    B -- Static SQL --> C[Write EXEC SQL Blocks]
    C --> D[SQL Precompiler]
    D --> E[Translated C Source]
    E --> F[C Compiler]
    F --> G[Object Code + SQLCA]
    G --> H[Linker with SQL Runtime]
    H --> I[Executable Program]
    I --> J[DBMS Engine]
    J --> K[Database]

    B -- Dynamic SQL --> L[Construct SQL String at Runtime]
    L --> M[PREPARE Statement]
    M --> N[EXECUTE or OPEN Cursor]
    N --> J

    B -- ODBC/JDBC API --> O[Load Driver Class]
    O --> P[DriverManager getConnection]
    P --> Q[Connection Object]
    Q --> R[Statement or PreparedStatement]
    R --> S[ExecuteQuery or ExecuteUpdate]
    S --> T[ResultSet Cursor]
    T --> U[Process Rows One by One]
    U --> V[Close ResultSet, Statement, Connection]
    V --> K

    style A fill:#e3f2fd,stroke:#0277bd,stroke-width:2px
    style B fill:#fff9c4,stroke:#f57f17,stroke-width:2px
    style D fill:#ffccbc,stroke:#bf360c,stroke-width:2px
