### Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

#### **Q1. [KTU University Exam ŌĆō May 2024]**
**Define impedance mismatch. Explain how cursors help overcome it in embedded SQL.**

**Model Answer:**

**Impedance Mismatch** is the fundamental conflict between the set-oriented, declarative nature of SQL (which manipulates entire relations as a single unit) and the record-oriented, imperative nature of host languages like C, COBOL, or Java (which operate on one variable or object at a time).

A **cursor** overcomes this mismatch by acting as a **bridge** that:

1. **DECLARE**s a logical pointer associated with a multi-row SELECT query.
2. **OPEN**s the cursor, which causes the DBMS to evaluate the query and materialize the result set.
3. **FETCH**es one row at a time from the result set into host-language variables ŌĆö converting the set-oriented output into a record-oriented stream.
4. **CLOSE**s the cursor when the application is done, releasing all associated memory and locks.

Thus, the cursor allows the host program to process SQL's set-based results **one record at a time**, which is exactly the granularity the host language requires.

> **Key Mark-Winning Phrase:** "Cursor acts as a pointer that traverses the result set row-by-row, resolving the set-vs-record impedance mismatch."

