#### **Q2. [KTU University Exam ŌĆō Dec 2023]**
**Differentiate between static embedded SQL and dynamic SQL.**

**Model Answer:**

| Parameter | Static Embedded SQL | Dynamic SQL |
|---|---|---|
| **When SQL is known** | At compile time | At runtime |
| **Preprocessor required?** | Yes (`EXEC SQL` blocks are precompiled) | No |
| **SQL statement source** | Hardcoded in source | Built as a string at runtime |
| **Execution steps** | Direct execution after compilation | `PREPARE` ŌåÆ `EXECUTE` |
| **Performance** | Faster (plan cached at compile time) | Slower (parsed every time, unless using `PREPARE`) |
| **Flexibility** | Low ŌĆö same statement always | High ŌĆö query can adapt to user input |
| **SQL injection risk** | None (input not concatenated) | High (string concatenation) |
| **Example use case** | Banking batch processing | Web search forms, ad-hoc reports |
| **KTU Tag** | "Static SQL ŌĆö Compile-time binding" | "Dynamic SQL ŌĆö Runtime binding" |

**Conclusion:** Static Embedded SQL is chosen for **performance-critical, fixed logic**, while Dynamic SQL is used when the **query text must adapt to runtime conditions**.

