#### **Question A [KTU University Exam ŌĆō Model Paper 2024]**

**(a)** Explain the architecture of ODBC with a neat diagram. Compare ODBC and JDBC. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a complete JDBC program in Java to (i) insert a new row into a `Student(sid, sname, marks)` table using `PreparedStatement`, and (ii) display all rows where `marks > 60` using a `ResultSet`. Handle all exceptions and close resources properly. **(7 marks)**

---

#### **Model Solution to Question A(a):**

**ODBC Architecture:**

ODBC (Open Database Connectivity) is a **Call Level Interface (CLI)** standard developed by Microsoft that allows any application to query any database through a uniform API. Its architecture has four layers:

1. **Application Layer:** The user program invokes ODBC API functions (e.g., `SQLExecDirect`, `SQLFetch`).
2. **Driver Manager Layer:** A system component that loads the appropriate driver for the target DBMS. It manages connection pooling, diagnostics, and driver registration.
3. **Driver Layer:** A vendor-supplied library (e.g., `sqlsrv32.dll` for SQL Server, `myodbc8w.dll` for MySQL) that translates generic ODBC calls into DBMS-specific native calls.
4. **Data Source Layer:** The actual DBMS engine and the physical database.

**Flow:**
$$
\text{App} \;\xrightarrow{\text{ODBC API}}\; \text{Driver Manager} \;\xrightarrow{\text{Dispatch}}\; \text{Vendor Driver} \;\xrightarrow{\text{Native Protocol}}\; \text{DBMS} \;\rightarrow\; \text{Database}
$$

**ODBC vs. JDBC Comparison Table:**

| Feature | ODBC | JDBC |
|---|---|---|
| **Language** | C-based, language-agnostic | Java-specific |
| **API Style** | Function calls (procedural) | Object methods (object-oriented) |
| **Driver Types** | Single standardized | 4 types (Type 1ŌĆō4) |
| **Platform** | Windows-centric (originally) | Cross-platform JVM |
| **Performance** | Fast (native code) | Type 4 driver is comparable |
| **Portability** | Requires DSN config per machine | JAR-based ŌĆö just include driver |
| **Standard** | SQL/CLI (ISO) | Java Community Process |
| **Memory Mgmt** | Manual | Automatic (Garbage Collector) |
| **Error Handling** | Return codes + `SQLGetDiagRec` | Exceptions (`SQLException`) |

**Conclusion:** ODBC is preferred in **legacy C/C++/Windows systems**, while JDBC is the **de-facto standard for modern Java/web applications**.

