#### **Model Solution to Question B(b):**

```c
/* Embedded SQL Program: Find students above class average */

#include <stdio.h>

EXEC SQL INCLUDE SQLCA;

EXEC SQL BEGIN DECLARE SECTION;
    int    v_sid;
    char   v_name[51];
    float  v_marks;
    float  v_avg;
EXEC SQL END DECLARE SECTION;

int main() {

    /* Connect to database */
    EXEC SQL CONNECT TO university_db USER sa USING password;

    /* Subquery to compute average marks */
    EXEC SQL SELECT AVG(marks) INTO :v_avg FROM Student;

    if (SQLCA.sqlcode != 0) {
        printf("Error computing average. SQLCODE = %d\n", SQLCA.sqlcode);
        return 1;
    }
    printf("Class average is: %.2f\n", v_avg);

    /* Declare cursor for the dynamic comparison */
    EXEC SQL DECLARE above_avg CURSOR FOR
        SELECT sid, sname, marks FROM Student WHERE marks > :v_avg;

    EXEC SQL OPEN above_avg;

    printf("\nStudents scoring above class average:\n");
    printf("--------------------------------------\n");

    while (1) {
        EXEC SQL FETCH above_avg INTO :v_sid, :v_name, :v_marks;

        /* SQLCA.sqlcode = 100 means "no more rows" */
        if (SQLCA.sqlcode == 100) {
            printf("(End of results)\n");
            break;
        }
        if (SQLCA.sqlcode != 0) {
            printf("Fetch error. SQLCODE = %d\n", SQLCA.sqlcode);
            break;
        }
        printf("SID: %d | Name: %s | Marks: %.2f\n", v_sid, v_name, v_marks);
    }

    EXEC SQL CLOSE above_avg;
    EXEC SQL DISCONNECT university_db;

    return 0;
}
```

**Explanation for marks:**

- `EXEC SQL INCLUDE SQLCA;` ŌĆö Includes the SQL Communication Area, which stores the status of the most recent SQL operation. **(1 mark)**
- `EXEC SQL BEGIN/END DECLARE SECTION;` ŌĆö Declares host variables for SQL use. **(0.5 mark)**
- `SELECT AVG(marks) INTO :v_avg;` ŌĆö Uses `INTO` to store a single-row aggregate into a host variable. **(1 mark)**
- `DECLARE above_avg CURSOR FOR ...` ŌĆö Declares a cursor for the multi-row query. **(1 mark)**
- `OPEN above_avg;` ŌĆö Executes the query and prepares the result set. **(0.5 mark)**
- `FETCH above_avg INTO :v_sid, :v_name, :v_marks;` ŌĆö Retrieves one row at a time. **(1 mark)**
- `SQLCA.sqlcode == 100` ŌĆö Detects end-of-data condition. **(1 mark)**
- `CLOSE above_avg;` ŌĆö Releases the cursor. **(0.5 mark)**
- `DISCONNECT` ŌĆö Cleanly terminates the session. **(0.5 mark)**

**Role of SQLCA in Error Handling (highlighted for examiner):**

The **SQL Communication Area (SQLCA)** is a system-managed data structure automatically included in the program. After every embedded SQL statement, the DBMS updates key fields:

- `sqlcode` ŌĆö A numeric status code:
  - `0` = success,
  - `> 0` = warning (e.g., `+100` = no more rows, `+12` = string truncation),
  - `< 0` = error (e.g., `-803` = duplicate key, `-911` = deadlock).
- `sqlerrm` ŌĆö A substructure with `sqlerrml` (length) and `sqlerrmc` (message text).
- `sqlerrd` ŌĆö A six-element array; `sqlerrd[2]` typically holds the **row count** of the most recent operation.

The application programmer must **always check `sqlcode`** after each SQL operation, as embedded SQL does **not throw exceptions** (unlike JDBC). This is a critical difference that KTU examiners love to highlight.

